{"id":"1609.07313","submitter":"Julien Scheibert","authors":"C Zouabi (LTDS), J Scheibert (LTDS), J Perret-Liaudet (LTDS)","title":"Memory in random bouncing ball dynamics","comments":"Final published version, 5 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":"EPL, European Physical Society/EDP Sciences/Societ{\\`a} Italiana\n  di Fisica/IOP Publishing, 2016, 115, pp.50006","doi":"10.1209/0295-5075/115/50006","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.class-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The bouncing of an inelastic ball on a vibrating plate is a popular model\nused in various fields, from granular gases to nanometer-sized mechanical\ncontacts. For random plate motion, so far, the model has been studied using\nPoincar{\\'e} maps in which the excitation by the plate at successive bounces is\nassumed to be a discrete Markovian (memoryless) process. Here, we investigate\nnumerically the behaviour of the model for continuous random excitations with\ntunable correlation time. We show that the system dynamics are controlled by\nthe ratio of the Markovian mean flight time of the ball and the mean time\nbetween successive peaks in the motion of the exciting plate. When this ratio,\nwhich depends on the bandwidth of the excitation signal, exceeds a certain\nvalue, the Markovian approach is appropriate; below, memory of preceding\nexcitations arises, leading to a significant decrease of the jump duration; at\nthe smallest values of the ratio, chattering occurs. Overall, our results open\nthe way for uses of the model in the low excitation regime, which is still\npoorly understood.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 23 Sep 2016 11:20:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 8 Dec 2016 12:28:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-12-09"}
{"id":"1609.07314","submitter":"Ka Lok Li","authors":"Ka Lok Li, Giulia Sgattoni, Hamzeh Sadeghisorkhani, Roland Roberts,\n  \\'Olafur Gudmundsson","title":"A double-correlation tremor-location method","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/gji/ggw453","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.geo-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A double-correlation method is introduced to locate tremor sources based on\nstacks of complex, doubly-correlated tremor records of multiple triplets of\nseismographs back projected to hypothetical source locations in a geographic\ngrid. Peaks in the resulting stack of moduli are inferred source locations. The\nstack of the moduli is a robust measure of energy radiated from a point source\nor point sources even when the velocity information is imprecise. Application\nto real data shows how double correlation focuses the source mapping compared\nto the common single correlation approach. Synthetic tests demonstrate the\nrobustness of the method and its resolution limitations which are controlled by\nthe station geometry, the finite frequency of the signal, the quality of the\nused velocity information and noise level. Both random noise and signal or\nnoise correlated at time shifts that are inconsistent with the assumed velocity\nstructure can be effectively suppressed. Assuming a surface-wave velocity, we\ncan constrain the source location even if the surface-wave component does not\ndominate. The method can also in principle be used with body waves in three\ndimensions, although this requires more data and seismographs placed near the\nsource for depth resolution.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 23 Sep 2016 11:20:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-12-21"}
